          "eventMetadata": {
            "context_description": "Recent U.S. economic data and consensus forecasts underpin the 92% market-implied probability against negative GDP growth in 2026. The Bureau of Economic Analysis reported 1.6% annualized real GDP expansion in Q1 2026, accelerating from 0.5% in Q4 2025, supported by gains in exports, business investment, and consumer spending. Major projections from the CBO, IMF, and private forecasters converge on 2.0–2.3% full-year growth, reflecting fiscal tailwinds from prior tax measures, AI-driven capital expenditures, and post-shutdown rebound effects that outweigh tariff pressures and labor-market moderation. Trader consensus prices in this baseline trajectory, with limited scope for contraction absent major geopolitical escalation or policy shocks.",
